diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with symptoms such as rash, oral ulcers, pleuritis leading to pleural effusion, and neurological manifestations including seizures. It may also present with arthritis, but true synovitis is less common.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) with Extra-Articular Manifestations
diagnoses.rationale: Though primarily known for its symmetrical synovitis, RA can have systemic involvement including skin manifestations (though typically not psoriasiform rash), pleural effusions, and occasionally, neurological complications.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis (PsA)
diagnoses.rationale: Psoriatic arthritis could account for the synovitis and psoriasiform rash. Less commonly, it can be associated with pleural effusions and neurological manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This vasculitis might cause oral ulcers, skin rashes, and can affect the central nervous system, potentially leading to seizures. It may also rarely cause synovitis and pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Known for affecting multiple organ systems. Can present with skin rashes similar to psoriasis, arthritis/synovitis, pulmonary involvement (potentially pleural effusion), and neurological involvement including seizures.

diagnoses.name: Seronegative Spondyloarthropathies
diagnoses.rationale: This group includes conditions such as ankylosing spondylitis and reactive arthritis, which can have overlapping features with PsA, including arthritis/synovitis and skin lesions, but oral ulcers and seizures are less commonly associated.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD can present with features of several connective tissue diseases, possibly explaining the range of symptoms but direct matches to each specific symptom are variable.

diagnoses.name: Lupus-like Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Drug-induced or environmental factors could cause a lupus-like syndrome, with a presentation similar to SLE, including rash, pleural effusion, and neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis (e.g., Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis)
diagnoses.rationale: Certain types of vasculitis could explain a broad constellation of symptoms due to small vessel inflammation affecting various organs including the skin, joints, lungs, and potentially the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Diseases (e.g., HIV, Hepatitis C)
diagnoses.rationale: Certain infections could potentially present with this complex symptomatology, especially as they can mimic autoimmune diseases, leading to dermatological presentations, arthritis, pleural effusions, and neurological manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can damage any part of the body, including skin, joints, and/or organs inside the body.

diagnoses.name: Lupus Nephritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the kidneys caused by systemic lupus erythematosus.

diagnoses.name: Hypersensitivity Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that occurs due to an allergic reaction to a drug or other foreign substance.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: A disease involving abnormal collections of inflammatory cells that can form as nodules in multiple organs.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels, causing changes in the blood vessel walls including thickening, weakening, narrowing, and scarring.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder that has signs and symptoms of a combination of disorders — primarily lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease in which the body's immune system attacks glands that secrete fluids, such as the tear and saliva glands.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: A chronic, potentially life-threatening condition caused by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) which interferes with the body's ability to fight infections.

diagnoses: Infectious Diseases (e.g., HIV, Hepatitis C, Endocarditis)
Evans Syndrome (Autoimmune Hemolytic Anemia with Immune Thrombocytopenia)
Cerebral Infection (such as Meningitis or Encephalitis)
Malignancy-related Leukopenia and Central Nervous System Involvement

diagnoses.name: Mastocytosis
diagnoses.description: Mastocytosis is a disorder characterized by mast cell proliferation within various organs, particularly the skin. Cutaneous forms can cause symptoms like dermatographism. Systemic involvement can affect liver function, potentially leading to abnormal liver enzymes, and can also cause hypoglycemia due to the release of mediators like histamine.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Fructose Intolerance
diagnoses.description: This genetic disorder affects fructose metabolism, leading to accumulation of toxic substances in the liver and kidneys. Symptoms include hypoglycemia, abnormal liver enzymes, and gastrointestinal issues. Vascular and skin anomalies could be indirectly related due to nutritional imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Glycogen Storage Disease
diagnoses.description: A group of inheritable diseases that result from defects in glycogen metabolism, leading to hypoglycemia and liver dysfunction (abnormal liver enzymes). Some types may indirectly affect the skin and vasculature due to metabolic disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that causes abnormal blood vessel formation. While primarily affecting vessels, it can have systemic implications including liver involvement (potentially affecting liver enzyme levels) and complications that might manifest as skin symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Urticaria
diagnoses.description: Though primarily a skin condition characterized by hives and itching, chronic forms can be associated with systemic symptoms. Dermatographism is a common feature. In severe cases, it might be associated with liver enzyme abnormalities due to systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Hepatic Encephalopathy
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by severe liver disease leading to brain dysfunction. It can present with hypoglycemia and abnormal liver enzymes. While not directly causing vascular anomalies or dermatographism, systemic illness can present with wide-ranging symptoms including those affecting the skin and circulation.

diagnoses.name: Wilson's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic disorder causing copper accumulation in the liver, brain, and other organs, leading to abnormal liver enzymes, psychiatric symptoms, and potentially dermatological manifestations. Hypoglycemia is less commonly associated but can occur due to liver damage.

diagnoses.name: Alpha-1 Antitrypsin Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition that can cause lung disease and liver disease (leading to abnormal liver enzymes), and less commonly, skin problems. It's a genetic disorder affecting the body's ability to produce a protein that protects the lungs and liver from damage.

diagnoses.name: Porphyria
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that can affect the nervous system and skin, leading to a wide range of symptoms including but not limited to abdominal pain, vomiting, neurological symptoms, and dermatological changes. Liver enzyme abnormalities may occur due to liver involvement.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect virtually any system in the body, including the skin, liver, and blood vessels. Symptoms might include dermatographism as a part of skin involvement, hypoglycemia, abnormal liver enzymes, and vascular anomalies due to systemic inflammation.

diagnoses: Bleeding Disorders (e.g., Hemophilia, Von Willebrand Disease)

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)
diagnoses.description: A condition that affects circulation (blood flow). It involves the nervous system and is characterized by the body's response to standing up. Symptoms include lightheadedness, fainting, and rapid heartbeat.

diagnoses.name: Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by deep swelling beneath the skin, especially around the eyes and lips. It can also affect the genitals, hands, and feet. Causes vary and include allergic reactions and hereditary factors.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A common type of anemia — a condition in which blood lacks adequate healthy red blood cells. Iron deficiency anemia is caused by a shortage of iron, leading to decreased production of hemoglobin, which carries oxygen.

diagnoses.name: Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: A neurological disorder characterized by an ongoing pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development.

diagnoses.name: Lymphadenitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the lymph nodes, typically a result of infection. It may occur in just one node or in a group of nodes.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks healthy tissue. It can affect the skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome (MCAS)
diagnoses.description: A condition in which mast cells inappropriately release chemical mediators, resulting in a range of chronic symptoms, some of which can be life-threatening.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemochromatosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that causes the body to absorb too much iron from the diet. The excess iron is stored in the body's organs, especially the liver, heart, and pancreas.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. Symptoms include highly flexible joints and stretchy, fragile skin.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An immune reaction to eating gluten, a protein found in wheat, barley, and rye. Over time, the immune reaction to eating gluten creates inflammation that damages the small intestine's lining.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a significant increase in heart rate when a person stands up, which can lead to symptoms like lightheadedness, fainting, and rapid heartbeat. It may associate with other symptoms due to underlying or comorbid conditions.

diagnoses.name: Endocrine Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions affecting the endocrine system can lead to symptoms like delayed puberty, irritability, and potentially contribute to conditions like folliculitis through hormonal imbalances. Common endocrine disorders include thyroid problems, adrenal insufficiency, and diabetes.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. Patients may report symptoms similar to those associated with POTS, including fatigue, dysgeusia, and irritability.

diagnoses.name: Eating Disorders
diagnoses.description: Disorders like anorexia nervosa or bulimia can lead to a wide range of symptoms, including delayed puberty due to malnutrition, dysgeusia as a result of dietary restrictions or purging behaviors, and irritability.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions where the immune system mistakenly attacks the body's own tissues, potentially contributing to symptoms like folliculitis (due to skin involvement), dysgeusia (through involvement of organs responsible for taste or secondary infections), and the autonomic dysfunction seen in POTS.

diagnoses.name: Nutritional Deficiencies
diagnoses.description: Lack of essential nutrients can contribute to delayed puberty, dysgeusia (especially deficiencies in zinc or vitamin B12), and general irritability. Correcting these deficiencies can alleviate some symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Neurological Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions affecting the nervous system, such as multiple sclerosis or autonomic neuropathy, might present with a broad range of symptoms including those similar to POTS, dysgeusia, and other sensory disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Psychiatric Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions like depression and anxiety can manifest with physical symptoms, including changes in heart rate (potentially mimicking POTS), irritability, and changes in appetite or weight that could indirectly influence puberty timing.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Diseases
diagnoses.description: Certain infections can lead to a diverse array of symptoms, including endocrine dysfunctions that might delay puberty, skin conditions like folliculitis, and taste disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Medication Side Effects
diagnoses.description: Various medications can have side effects that mimic the symptoms listed, including dysgeusia, irritability, and hormone imbalances that could delay puberty or affect skin health, contributing to issues like folliculitis.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic disorder that results in recurrent attacks of angioedema, or episodes of swelling. This condition might also involve skin lesions and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the body's moisture-producing glands. Primary symptoms include dry eyes and dry mouth, but it can also lead to more systemic symptoms like fatigue and joint pain.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect the connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. Symptoms can include easy bruising, hypermobility, and skin that stretches easily.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Idiopathic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition where hives or urticaria persist for six weeks or more without an identified cause. Symptoms can include severe itching, angioedema, and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease where the body's immune system mistakenly attacks healthy tissue. It can affect the skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs. Symptoms include fatigue, joint pain, rash, and fever.

diagnoses.name: Graves' Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that results in the overproduction of thyroid hormones (hyperthyroidism). Symptoms can include bulging eyes, weight loss, anxiety, irritability, and skin rash.

diagnoses.name: Mastocytosis
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by the accumulation of mast cells in the skin and other organs. Symptoms can include itching, abdominal discomfort, hypersensitivity reactions, and anaphylaxis.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can affect any organ. Symptoms depend on the organs affected but can include red spots on the skin, numb or cold limbs, and loss of pulse.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders where part of the body's immune system is missing or does not function properly. Frequent infections, delayed growth, and autoimmunity are common symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Hepatitis C
diagnoses.description: A viral infection that causes liver inflammation, sometimes leading to serious liver damage. The hepatitis C virus spreads through contaminated blood. While many people with Hepatitis C experience no symptoms, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer over time.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells. These excess cells thicken the blood, slowing its flow, and can cause complications like clotting or bleeding. Telangiectasias, headache, fatigue, and insomnia may be present.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. Patients may experience insomnia and irritability due to the pain and lack of restful sleep.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. The fatigue worsens with physical or mental activity but doesn't improve with rest. Muscle pain, sleep disturbances, and irritability are common.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.description: A mental health disorder characterized by persistently depressed mood or loss of interest in activities, causing significant impairment in daily life. Symptoms can include insomnia, irritability, and physical symptoms such as muscle pain.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disease that causes hardening and tightening of the skin and connective tissues. It can cause telangiectasias, muscle pain, and may affect internal organs. Fatigue and sleep disturbances are also common symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system that disrupts the flow of information within the brain, and between the brain and body. Symptoms can be wide-ranging, including muscle pain, fatigue, and sleep disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Common symptoms include fatigue, muscle pain, irritability, and sleep disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Obstructive Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by repetitive episodes of upper airway obstruction during sleep, leading to breathing pauses. Symptoms include daytime fatigue, irritability, and insomnia.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. Symptoms can include muscle pain, fatigue, and skin manifestations such as telangiectasias.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: A group of mental health disorders characterized by feelings of anxiety and fear. Anxiety can cause muscle tension and pain, sleep disturbances like insomnia, and irritability.

diagnoses: Inflammatory bowel disease (e.g., Crohn's disease, Ulcerative colitis)

diagnoses.name: Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: A brain disorder marked by an ongoing pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development.

diagnoses.name: Kounis Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Also known as allergic myocardial infarction or allergic angina syndrome, it's a condition where acute coronary syndromes are triggered by allergic reactions.

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection (UTI)
diagnoses.description: An infection in any part of the urinary system, the kidneys, bladder, or urethra.

diagnoses.name: Leukopenia
diagnoses.description: A condition where the white blood cell count (leukocytes) is lower than normal, which can weaken the body’s immune system.

diagnoses.name: Malabsorption Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A disorder affecting the intestinal absorption of nutrients, leading to deficiencies and gastrointestinal symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, often leading to malabsorption.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD)
diagnoses.description: An umbrella term used to describe disorders that involve chronic inflammation of the digestive tract, such as Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and damage to various body systems, including joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: An extreme and severe allergic reaction that can lead to life-threatening symptoms, including cardiovascular collapse which is related to Kounis Syndrome.
symptoms: Kounis Syndrome (as part of anaphylactic reaction)

diagnoses.name: Hodgkin's Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of lymphoma, which is a cancer of the lymphatic system. It can affect the body's ability to fight infection and can cause leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones, potentially leading to a variety of symptoms, including those presented.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A metabolic disorder characterized by high blood sugar levels over a prolonged period. Poor control can lead to a range of complications that may correlate with the given symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Congestive Heart Failure
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition in which the heart doesn't pump blood as well as it should. This can lead to fluid build-up, causing nausea and worsening chronic kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Renal Failure
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys don't work as well as they should. It can lead to a build-up of toxins in the body, potentially worsening or causing dyslipidemia and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, leading to widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs, including the kidneys and potentially causing angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reactions
diagnoses.description: An exaggerated immune response to foreign substances. It could explain the sinutitis and angioedema, especially if there is an allergy to medications used to treat other listed symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Acute Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the sinuses that can cause sinus congestion, pain, and more systemic symptoms like nausea, possibly aggravating or being aggravated by other chronic conditions.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.description: A common condition in which the long-term force of the blood against your artery walls is high enough that it may eventually cause health problems, such as heart disease and is often associated with chronic kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition causing swelling in various body parts, including the extremities, face, and throat. It's important to consider, especially if angioedema is recurrent and unexplained by other causes.

diagnoses.name: Medication Side Effects
diagnoses.description: Certain medications prescribed for dyslipidemia, hypertension, or chronic kidney disease may cause side effects such as nausea or angioedema, indicating a need to review the patient's current treatment regimen.

diagnoses.name: Marfan Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that affects the body's connective tissue, potentially leading to features like aneurysms and eye irritation due to its impact on various body systems.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. May contribute to osteoporosis and aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease (ADPKD)
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder characterized by the growth of numerous cysts in the kidneys, potentially leading to chronic kidney disease. The condition might also be associated with aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Loeys-Dietz Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder affecting the body's connective tissue, characterized by features such as widely spaced eyes, which could be misinterpreted as eye irritation, and a predisposition to aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition characterized by a gradual loss of kidney function. It can contribute to mineral and bone disorder, increasing the risk of osteoporosis.

diagnoses.name: Fibromuscular Dysplasia
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes abnormal growth or development of cells in the walls of blood vessels, which can lead to the formation of aneurysms, and potentially affect kidney function leading to chronic kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands that provide lubrication to the eyes and mouth. The chronic inflammation can lead to symptoms such as irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Primary Hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the parathyroid glands in which one or more of the parathyroid glands produces too much parathyroid hormone, leading to calcium imbalance, potentially resulting in osteoporosis and kidney disease.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can cause narrowing, blockage, or the weakening of blood vessels, potentially leading to aneurysms and affecting the kidneys.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.description: Chronic high blood pressure can lead to damage of blood vessels and organs, including the kidneys, and contribute to the risk of developing aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Otitis Externa
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the external auditory canal, often associated with infection and can cause difficulty focusing due to discomfort and possible fever.

diagnoses.name: Visual Disturbance
diagnoses.description: Difficulty focusing vision can be a sign of various ocular problems, ranging from refractive errors to more serious conditions like glaucoma or macular degeneration.

diagnoses.name: Leukoplakia
diagnoses.description: A condition involving white patches or plaques on the mucous membranes of the oral cavity, often benign but can be precancerous, indicating a need for evaluation.

diagnoses.name: Heat Stroke (Hyperthermia)
diagnoses.description: A severe form of hyperthermia that occurs when the body absorbs more heat than it can dissipate, often resulting in high fever, confusion, and can lead to multiple organ dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Skin Tags (Acrochordons)
diagnoses.description: Benign skin growths that typically do not cause symptoms unless irritated or aesthetically concerning, commonly occurring in areas of friction.

diagnoses.name: Oral Thrush
diagnoses.description: An overgrowth of Candida yeast in the mouth, which can sometimes present similarly to leukoplakia with white patches.

diagnoses.name: Conjunctivitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation or infection of the outer membrane of the eyeball and the inner eyelid, which can cause discomfort and visual disturbance.

diagnoses.name: Squamous Cell Carcinoma
diagnoses.description: A form of skin cancer that may present with lesions or plaques that could resemble leukoplakia or skin tags; hyperthermia could be an indirect sign if associated with systemic illness.

diagnoses.name: Keratoconjunctivitis Sicca (Dry Eye Syndrome)
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the tear film due to tear deficiency or excessive evaporation causing discomfort and visual disturbance.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.description: A condition that results from excessive loss of body water, capable of leading to symptoms of hyperthermia and contributing to ocular symptoms like difficulty focusing.

diagnoses: Oral squamous cell carcinoma (for leukoplakia, especially when non-resolving)
Hyperlipidemia-associated conditions (since dyslipidemia itself is a condition, focusing on its complications)
Autoimmune Diseases (e.g., Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, Rheumatoid Arthritis)

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that leads to abnormal blood vessel formation, leading to symptoms like arteriovenous malformations and easy bleeding.

diagnoses.name: Common Variable Immune Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by decreased levels of several immunoglobulin classes, leading to an increased risk of infections and possibly related to laryngitis due to frequent infections.

diagnoses.name: Selective Immunoglobulin Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition where one or more of the immunoglobulin types are missing or below normal levels, potentially contributing to both decreased and increased immunoglobulins in different classes.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Lymphoproliferative Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the immune system that leads to increased levels of lymphocytes and can involve abnormal immunoglobulin levels, potentially explaining the fluctuating immunoglobulin levels.

diagnoses.name: Wiskott-Aldrich Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, inherited immune disorder characterized by easy bleeding, eczema, and a high susceptibility to infection, possibly connected to the increased immunoglobulin levels as a response to frequent infections.

diagnoses.name: Churg-Strauss Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder characterized by increased eosinophils. It's associated with vasculitis, which could explain arteriovenous malformations and the alteration in immunoglobulin levels.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Granulomatous Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder affecting phagocyte function, leading to increased susceptibility to infections, which could contribute to phenomena such as increased or decreased immunoglobulins.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: Cancer of the lymphatic system can affect immune function, potentially leading to symptoms such as changes in immunoglobulin levels, arteriovenous malformations through direct involvement or secondary effects, and easy bleeding.

diagnoses.name: Glanzmann Thrombasthenia
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic platelet disorder that results in easy bleeding. While it doesn't directly account for all listed symptoms, its association with bleeding could be relevant in the context of arteriovenous malformations.

diagnoses.name: Goodpasture Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where antibodies attack the lungs and kidneys, but it's included here as autoimmune disorders can sometimes present with a wide range of symptoms, including variable immunoglobulin levels.

diagnoses: Bacterial or Fungal Skin Infections leading to Folliculitis

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: Migraine headaches can cause severe throbbing pain or a pulsing sensation, usually on one side of the head. It's often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine attacks can cause significant pain for hours to days and can be so severe that the pain is disabling.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers and causes communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body. Symptoms include numbness, weakness, and problems with coordination and balance.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.details: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. A stroke is a medical emergency, and prompt treatment is crucial. Symptoms can include trouble speaking and understanding what others are saying, paralysis or numbness of the face, arm or leg, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.details: Diabetic neuropathy is a type of nerve damage that can occur if you have diabetes. High blood sugar (glucose) can injure nerves throughout your body. Diabetic neuropathy most often damages nerves in your legs and feet. Symptoms can include numbness, reduced ability to feel pain or temperature changes, and muscle weakness.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some are noncancerous (benign), and some are cancerous (malignant). Symptoms can include headaches, seizures, personality or memory changes, nausea or vomiting, fatigue, and sleeping problems.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: Anemia is a condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues. Having anemia can make you feel tired and weak. Other symptoms can include headache and dizziness.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.details: Lyme disease is a bacterial infection you get from the bite of an infected tick. The first symptom is usually a red rash, which may look like a bull's eye. But it can also cause symptoms like fever, chills, fatigue, body aches, headache, neck stiffness, and facial paralysis.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.details: Fibromyalgia is a disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. Researchers believe that fibromyalgia amplifies painful sensations by affecting the way your brain and spinal cord process painful and nonpainful signals. Symptoms include widespread pain, fatigue, and cognitive difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.details: Hypothyroidism, or underactive thyroid, is a condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones. Hypothyroidism's signs and symptoms may include fatigue, increased sensitivity to cold, constipation, dry skin, weight gain, puffy face, hoarseness, muscle weakness, elevated blood cholesterol level, pain, stiffness or swelling in your joints, and heavier than normal menstrual periods.

diagnoses.name: Transverse Myelitis
diagnoses.details: Transverse myelitis is an inflammation of both sides of one section of the spinal cord. This neurological disorder often damages the insulating material covering nerve cell fibers (myelin). Transverse myelitis interrupts the messages that the spinal cord nerves send throughout the body. This can cause pain, muscle weakness, paralysis, sensory problems, or bladder and bowel dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that is often accompanied by visual disturbances (scotoma) and other sensory symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms can include headache, aphasia, and other neurological deficits.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, where symptoms such as aphasia and visual disturbances may occur briefly and usually resolve within 24 hours.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Symptoms can include headaches, seizures, and cognitive or speech disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV)
diagnoses.description: A disorder arising in the inner ear that can cause vertigo. It is often triggered by changes in the position of the head.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inner ear disorder that causes severe dizziness (vertigo), ringing in the ears (tinnitus), hearing loss, and a feeling of fullness or congestion in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Neuronitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the vestibular nerve, a nerve in the ear that helps control balance. Symptoms include sudden, severe vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms can include fatigue, difficulty walking, and speech disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the fluid and membranes (meninges) surrounding the brain and spinal cord. Symptoms can include headache, fever, and stiff neck.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

diagnoses.name: Lupus erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of your body. It's characterized by symptoms like skin rashes, oral ulcers, and potentially pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and skin rashes. It may present with symptoms like Gottron's papules, heliotrope rash, and could potentially cause nonscarring alopecia.

diagnoses.name: Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory condition that affects the skin, hair, nails, and mucous membranes. It can cause a characteristic rash, oral ulcers, and nonscarring alopecia.

diagnoses.name: Drug reactions
diagnoses.description: Adverse reactions to medications can cause a variety of symptoms including maculopapular rash, oral ulcers, and in rare cases, other symptoms like pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Pemphigus vulgaris
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that can cause blistering and sores on the skin and mucous membranes, including oral ulcers. It may be associated with skin rashes but is not typically associated with pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, primarily the lungs and lymph glands. Skin manifestations like rashes and nonscarring alopecia may occur, and pleural effusion is a possible complication.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson syndrome
diagnoses.description: A severe skin reaction often to mediations or infections. It can cause a painful rash that spreads and blisters, including on the mucous membranes.

diagnoses.name: Systemic sclerosis (scleroderma)
diagnoses.description: A group of autoimmune diseases that cause changes in the skin, blood vessels, muscles, and internal organs. Skin changes such as rashes and other symptoms including pleural effusion can occur.

diagnoses.name: Viral infections (e.g., HIV, Hepatitis C)
diagnoses.description: Certain viral infections can cause a range of symptoms including rashes, lichen planus, oral ulcers, and more. HIV particularly can lead to nonscarring alopecia.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing inflammation in blood vessels. This condition can result in a wide variety of signs and symptoms, including oral ulcers, skin rashes, and more rarely, pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with discoid rash, nonscarring alopecia, nasal ulcers, and hemolytic anemia among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Discoid Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily affecting the skin (discoid rash), systemic involvement can occasionally occur.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Rarely, can show systemic features including skin rashes and blood abnormalities like hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily affects moisture-producing glands, but systemic features can mimic those of lupus including rash and hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: Inflammatory disease known for distinctive skin rash and muscle weakness, but can have systemic features like hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Shows features of various autoimmune diseases including SLE, scleroderma, and polymyositis, potentially involving skin, blood, and more.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body, can lead to skin rashes, sores in the mouth and nose, and other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Polymyositis
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily affecting muscle, can have associated skin rashes and systemic features similar to those of dermatomyositis.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma
diagnoses.rationale: An autoimmune disease with skin involvement that can occasionally manifest systemic features including anemia.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can cause a wide range of symptoms depending on the organs affected, including skin rashes and anemia.

diagnoses: Hepatitis B or C with Cryoglobulinemia

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with leukopenia, synovitis (inflammation of the joint linings), nasal ulcers, a photosensitive rash, and arthropathy (joint disease).

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: While more commonly associated with symmetric arthropathy and synovitis, it can occasionally present with leukopenia and rarer systemic manifestations such as skin and mucosal ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily affects the body's moisture-producing glands and can lead to arthropathy. Though less common, it may present with leukopenia, and skin manifestations might mimic photosensitivity.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: Characterized by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash that is often photosensitive. Joint inflammation and other symptoms might overlap with the symptoms listed.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.rationale: Can cause skin changes that might appear as a photosensitive rash, along with arthropathy. Less commonly, it may lead to leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This disease has overlapping features of lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis, including leukopenia, arthropathy, and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: A group of disorders that involve inflammation of the blood vessels. Certain types can lead to skin ulcers and rashes, joint pain, and sometimes affect white blood cell count.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This rare disorder causes blood vessel inflammation throughout the body, including painful mouth and genital ulcers, skin lesions, and potentially joint symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced Lupus
diagnoses.rationale: Some medications can induce a lupus-like syndrome, presenting with symptoms such as rash, arthropathy, and occasionally leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Relapsing Polychondritis
diagnoses.rationale: This rare disease involves recurrent episodes of inflammation and deterioration of cartilage. It can sometimes have overlapping symptoms with the ones listed, though it's more associated with cartilage than the specific symptoms given.
